at the ideological rifts of the period inspired the adoption and adaptation of newly available technologies to encourage social mobilization and political action, a function performed for much of the previous century by independent documentary film. Positioning documentary film and digital media side by side in the political sphere, Fallon asserts that "truth" now lies in a new set of media forms and discursive practices that implicitly shape the documentation of everything from widespread cultural spectacles like wars and presidential elections to more invisible or isolated phenomena like the Abu Ghraib torture scandal or the "fake news" debates of 2016.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCommunication. Mass media. 0aDigital mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 0aDocumentary mass mediazUnited Statesy21st century. 0aMass mediaxObjectivityzUnited Statesy21st century. 0aMotion pictures. 0aOnline social networksxPolitical aspectsy21st century. 0aPolitical institutions and public administration (General). 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Documentary.2bisacsh  a21st century.  aabu ghraib torture.  abig data.  acrowdsourcing.  acultural integration.  adata visualization.  adigital platforms.  adocumentary film tradition.  adocumentary film.  aevolution.  afake news.  aformative influence.  aideological rifts.  akey media forms.  aphotography.  apolitical action.  apolitical conflict.  apolitical rupture.  apresidential elections.  ascandal.  asocial networking.  avideo games.  avirtual environments.  awars.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEB